comments.body:
Thanks [~eepayne]
bq. I would say it would be best to save the recomputed user AM limit to all users objects whenever LeafQueue#getUserAMResourceLimitPerPartition is called, but that may cause a significant performance hit. Even so, I think this option is the cleanest and the performance hit may not be that bad.
This seems better as per me.

Some comments in code
1. In LeafQueue, below map is newly introduced.
{code}
	  private Map<String, Resource> amResourceLimitPerUserPerPartition =
	      new HashMap<String, Resource>();
{code}
I think we can avoid this storage in LeafQueue. We could add a new item in {{ResourceUsage}} class. Currently we have 
{code}
  public enum ResourceType {
    // CACHED_USED and CACHED_PENDING may be read by anyone, but must only
    // be written by ordering policies
    USED(0), PENDING(1), AMUSED(2), RESERVED(3), CACHED_USED(4), CACHED_PENDING(
        5), AMLIMIT(6), MIN_RESOURCE(7), MAX_RESOURCE(8), EFF_MIN_RESOURCE(
            9), EFF_MAX_RESOURCE(10);
{code}
We could add a new flag AMLIMIT_PERUSER and store it in *ResourceUsage*?
2. in below code
{code}
722	      preWeighteduserAMLimit =
723	          Resources.lessThanOrEqual(resourceCalculator, lastClusterResource,
724	          preWeighteduserAMLimit,
725	          getAMResourceLimitPerPartition(nodePartition))
726	          ? preWeighteduserAMLimit
727	              : getAMResourceLimitPerPartition(nodePartition);
{code}
could we use {{Resources.min}} instead of ternary operator?
3. In {{UserInfo}}, we could avoid {{amLimitPerUserPerPartition}} if comment #1 is accepted.
4. In {{getAmLimitPerUserPerPartition}},  below comment says that
{noformat}
116	    // If the most recent per-user AM limit is not available, use the most
117	    // recent Max AM Resource limit that was computed for this user. If this
118	    // value is retrieved, there is no need to multiply it's weight.
{noformat}
But if user has a low user-weight and if we give latest value, how far off it could be in worst case?

Thanks [~eepayne].

Few more minor comments

# In LQ,
{code}
userAMLimit = Resources.lessThanOrEqual(resourceCalculator, lastClusterResource,
	          userAMLimit, getAMResourceLimitPerPartition(nodePartition)) ?
	          userAMLimit : getAMResourceLimitPerPartition(nodePartition);
{code}
I think we can use Resources.min here also.
# I think its an existing bug. In above code, {{getAMResourceLimitPerPartition(nodePartition)}} is returning stored Resource object (not clone). And this *userAMLimit* is later set to {{user.getResourceUsage()}} etc. Its better to use Resources.clone on this object, correct?
